@endnode
@node installation "Installation"

You should install both @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} and @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} on each Amiga you
expect to use for initiating keyboard and mouse input, and each Amiga
you want to control remotely. You should also install @{"VReboot" link VReboot} on each
Amiga you want to reboot without using the keyboard on that Amiga.

For installation details for each program, read the corresponding
program installation instructions:

	@{"Ventriloquist Installation" link Ventriloquist.Installation}
	@{"VPrefs Installation" link VPrefs.Installation}
	@{"VReboot Installation" link VReboot.Installation}

@endnode
@node quickstart "Quick Start"

1.	Make sure Amiga Envoy is properly set up and running on all
	Amigas where you intend to use this software.

2.	@{"Install" link Installation} @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} and @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} on each Amiga where you intend
	to use this software.

3.	Choose an Amiga you want to control from (host A), and an
	Amiga you want to control (Host B).

4.	Run @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} on Host A.

5.	Click on the Add... button next to the @{"Server list" link vprefs.windows.main.serverlist} in the
	@{"VPrefs main window" link vprefs.windows.main}, which will make the @{"VPrefs server window" link VPrefs.windows.server}
	appear.

6.	Type in the host name of Host B into the @{"Server Name" link vprefs.windows.server.servername} gadget in the
	@{"VPrefs server window" link VPrefs.windows.server}.

7.	Select the @{"Hot Key" link vprefs.windows.server.hotkey} checkbox in the @{"VPrefs server window" link VPrefs.windows.server}. This will
	use "left_amiga F10" as the default hot key.

8.	Click on the @{"Use button" link vprefs.windows.server.usebutton} in the @{"VPrefs server window" link VPrefs.windows.server}.

9.	Click on the @{"Save button" link vprefs.windows.main.savebutton} in the @{"VPrefs main window" link vprefs.windows.main}.

10.	Run @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} on both Host A and Host B.

11.	On Host A, press F10 while holding down the left Amiga key. Any
	keyboard or mouse input after you do this will appear on Host B.

12.	To switch back to controlling Host A, press F10 while holding
	down the left Amiga key again.

@endnode
@node ventriloquist "Ventriloquist Program"

Ventriloquist is a commodity program that watches to see when you type a
special hot key or move the mouse to the edge of the screen. When you do
this, Ventriloquist will connect to another copy of itself running on
another Amiga and will cooperate with that copy to make it look as if
you were directly using the keyboard and mouse on that Amiga.

For more details on commodities, see your Workbench User's Guide.

Ventriloquist has no visible user interface. It can be controlled
with the included @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} preferences program and with the Exchange
commodity program supplied with Workbench 2.04 or later.

	@{" Ventriloquist Installation " link ventriloquist.installation}
	@{" Ventriloquist Startup " link ventriloquist.startup}
	@{" Ventriloquist Termination " link ventriloquist.termination}

@endnode
@node ventriloquist.installation "Ventriloquist Installation"

Install @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} on each Amiga where you want to use it by copying
it to your SYS:Tools/Commodities drawer, or to an alternate location of
your own choice. You can copy it by dragging the icon with the mouse, or
by typing this shell command:

	Copy Ventriloquist#? SYS:Tools/Commodities

Modify your system to run Ventriloquist at startup time by adding this
command to your S:user-startup file:

	Run >NIL: Ventriloquist

If you install Ventriloquist someplace other than in SYS:Tools/Commodities,
make sure the directory you installed it in is in your command path, or you
will need to change the command shown above to include the directory name.

@endnode
@node ventriloquist.startup "Ventriloquist Startup"

@{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} can be started either from a shell or from Workbench.

When run from a shell, Ventriloquist uses this command line template:

	CX_PRIORITY/N/K

	CX_PRIORITY sets the commodity priority of Ventriloquist. If
	you also run other commodity programs on both Amigas, set this
	higher than the other commodities' priorities if you want the
	hot key to be passed to the other Amiga. This defaults to 0.

When run from Workbench, Ventriloquist supports the CX_PRIORITY and
DONOTWAIT tool types, just like the commodity programs supplied with
Workbench.

@endnode
@node ventriloquist.termination "Ventriloquist Termination"

You can terminate @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} any of several ways:

	1. Run it again (which will cause it to exit),
	2. Remove it using the Exchange program in SYS:Tools/Commodities, or
	3. Send it a Control-C.

@endnode
@node vprefs "VPrefs Program"

VPrefs is a preferences program that lets you control how @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist}
will work. If you're already familiar with the way the standard Amiga
preferences programs work under Workbench 2.04 and above, this program
should look familiar to you.

For more details on preferences, see your Workbench User's Guide.

	@{" VPrefs Installation " link vprefs.installation}
	@{" VPrefs Startup " link vprefs.startup}
	@{" VPrefs Termination " link vprefs.termination}
	@{" VPrefs Windows " link vprefs.windows}
	@{" VPrefs Menus " link vprefs.menus}

@endnode
@node vprefs.installation "VPrefs Installation"

Install @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} on each Amiga where you want to use it by copying it to
your SYS:Prefs drawer, or to an alternate location of your own choice.
You can copy it by dragging the icon with the mouse, or by typing this
shell command:

	Copy VPrefs#? SYS:Prefs

@endnode
@node vprefs.startup "VPrefs Startup"

@{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} can be started either from a shell or from Workbench.

When run from a shell, VPrefs uses this command line template:

	FROM,EDIT/S,USE/S,SAVE/S,PUBSCREEN/K

	FROM lets you specify a preferences file to open. This must be
	a file that was previously saved with the @{"Project/Save As..." link vprefs.menus.Project.SaveAs}
	menu option in VPrefs. If the FROM option is not provided, the
	default preferences file will be opened.

	EDIT will open the @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main} for editing. This is done
	by default, unless you specify the SAVE or USE option.

	USE will use the file specified with the FROM option without
	opening the VPrefs main window.

	SAVE will save the file specified with the FROM option without
	opening the VPrefs main window.

	PUBSCREEN tells VPrefs which public screen to open its window on.
	This defaults to the workbench screen.

When run from Workbench, VPrefs supports the ACTION=EDIT, ACTION=USE,
ACTION=SAVE, and PUBSCREEN tool types, just like the preferences programs
supplied with Workbench.

@endnode
@node vprefs.termination "VPrefs Termination"

You can terminate @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} any of several ways:

	1. Click on the @{"Save" link vprefs.windows.main.savebutton}, @{"Use" link vprefs.windows.main.usebutton}, or @{"Cancel" link vprefs.windows.main.cancelbutton} button in the
	   @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main},
	2. Select the @{"Project/Quit" link vprefs.menus.project.quit} menu option, or
	3. Send it a Control-C.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows "VPrefs Windows"

@{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} uses a single main window, with other special-purpose windows
occasionally displayed as needed. The following sections describe these
windows and their contents.

	@{" VPrefs Main Window " link vprefs.windows.main}
	@{" VPrefs Server Window " link vprefs.windows.server}

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.main "VPrefs Main Window"

The @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} main window contains several gadgets that let you determine
how @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} will work. This window contains these gadgets:

	@{" Server List " link vprefs.windows.main.ServerList}
	@{" Client List " link vprefs.windows.main.ClientList}
	@{" Client Authorization " link vprefs.windows.main.ClientAuthorization}
	@{" Save Button " link vprefs.windows.main.SaveButton}
	@{" Use Button " link vprefs.windows.main.UseButton}
	@{" Cancel Button " link vprefs.windows.main.CancelButton}

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.main.serverlist "VPrefs Main Window: Server List"

	A server is another Amiga that you can control from your
	Amiga using @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist}. The server list shows the servers
	you can control with your Amiga. Next to this list, there are
	Add, Edit, and Delete buttons. The Add button opens the
	@{"VPrefs server window" link VPrefs.windows.server} to let you add another Amiga to the list
	of servers. The Edit button opens the VPrefs server window to
	let you change the details about a server, and the Delete button
	lets you remove a server from the list. You must select a server
	in the server list before you can edit it or delete it.

	For each server, the server name and the mouse movements and/or
	hot key that can be used to switch to that server are shown.
	The mouse movements are shown as a combination of L, R, U,
	and/or D, followed by a number. The letters represent Left,
	Right, Up, or Down, and the number represents the threshold
	used to determine how fast the mouse must be moving to switch
	from one Amiga to another. For example, L-0 means that you can
	switch to the server by moving the mouse off the left edge of
	the screen, as slowly as you wish. L-100 would mean that you
	can switch by jamming the mouse fairly fast against the left
	edge of the screen, but you could avoid switching by moving
	slower. You can switch back to the Amiga you're sitting at by
	moving the mouse in the opposite direction.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.main.clientlist "VPrefs Main Window: Client List"

	A client is another Amiga that can control your Amiga using
	@{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist}. The client list shows all clients you will
	allow to control your Amiga. Next to this list, there are Add
	and Delete buttons. The Add button opens a requester to let
	you choose another Amiga to add to the list of clients, and
	the Delete button removes a client from the list. You must
	click on a client in the list before you can delete it.

	The client list is only used if @{"Client Authorization" link vprefs.windows.main.ClientAuthorization} is set
	to Accept Listed Clients.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.main.clientAuthorization "VPrefs Main Window: Client Authorization"

	Choose which other Amigas can control your Amiga using
	@{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist}. If you choose Accept All Clients, any other
	Amiga on the network will be able to control your Amiga. If
	you choose Accept Listed Clients, only those listed in the
	@{"Client list" link vprefs.windows.main.Clientlist} will be able to control your Amiga. If you choose
	Don't Accept Any Clients, no other Amigas will be able to
	control yours.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.main.savebutton "VPrefs Main Window: Save Button"

	Implement and save all changes you have made and close the
	@{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main}. These changes will be used immediately
	by @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist}.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.main.usebutton "VPrefs Main Window: Use Button"

	Implement all changes you have made without saving them and
	close the @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main}. These changes will be used
	immediately by @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist}. Rebooting the Amiga returns
	to the default or previously saved changes.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.main.cancelbutton "VPrefs Main Window: Cancel Button"

	Close the @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main} without making any changes to the
	way @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} operates. The settings in effect before you
	ran @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} will remain in effect. This does the same thing as
	the @{"Project/Quit" link vprefs.menus.project.quit} menu option.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server "VPrefs Server Window"

The VPrefs server window contains several gadgets that show you the
detailed setup for a specific server, either a new one being added or
an existing one being changed. This window contains these gadgets:

	@{" Server Name " link vprefs.windows.server.servername}
	@{" Mouse Left, Right, Up, and Down " link vprefs.windows.server.mousedirection}
	@{" Threshold " link vprefs.windows.server.threshold}
	@{" Hot Key " link vprefs.windows.server.hotkey}
	@{" Mouse Motion " link vprefs.windows.server.mousemotion}
	@{" Feedback " link vprefs.windows.server.feedback}
	@{" Use Button " link vprefs.windows.server.usebutton}
	@{" Cancel Button " link vprefs.windows.server.cancelbutton}

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.servername "VPrefs Server Window: Server Name"

	The name of another Amiga you want to control from your Amiga.
	This may be any Amiga on the Amiga Envoy network, but you must
	also run @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} on the other Amiga to tell it to accept input
	from your Amiga.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.Mousedirection "VPrefs Server Window: Mouse Left, Right, Up, and Down"

	Determine which direction, if any, you can move the mouse
	pointer off the edge of the screen to switch control from
	your Amiga to the other Amiga you named as the server.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.Threshold "VPrefs Server Window: Threshold"

	Determine how fast you need to move the mouse off the edge
	of the screen before @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} will switch control to
	the other Amiga you named as the server. Think of this as the
	height of a speed bump at the edge of the screen. If you're
	moving too slow, you won't make it over the bump, but if you're
	moving faster, you'll switch control to the other machine.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.HotKey "VPrefs Server Window: Hot Key"

	Determine whether you can use a hot key to switch control
	between Amigas, and which key combination you can use. For
	more information about hot keys, see the section on commodities
	in your Workbench User's Guide.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.MouseMotion "VPrefs Server Window: Mouse Motion"

	Determine whether all mouse movements will be sent to the
	server (Smooth) or whether intermediate movements will be
	skipped over to allow the network to keep up (Fast).

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.Feedback "VPrefs Server Window: Feedback"

	Determine what kind of feedback will let you know that keyboard
	and mouse input is being sent to another Amiga. The available
	choices are: Window (for a window to appear on the screen), Beep
	(for the Amiga losing input to beep), or None (no feedback). In
	all three cases, the Workbench screen title bar will show the
	Ventriloquist @{"copyright" link copyright} information.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.UseButton "VPrefs Server Window: Use Button"

	Add the changes you've made in the @{"VPrefs server window" link VPrefs.windows.server} to
	the @{"server list" link vprefs.windows.main.serverlist} in the @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main}, and close the
	VPrefs server window.

@endnode
@node vprefs.windows.server.CancelButton "VPrefs Server Window: Cancel Button"

	Close the @{"VPrefs server window" link VPrefs.windows.server} without making any changes
	to the @{"server list" link vprefs.windows.main.serverlist} in the @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main}.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus "VPrefs Menus"

The @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main} has these menu options:

	Project
	    @{" Open... " link vprefs.menus.project.open}
	    @{" Save As... " link vprefs.menus.project.SaveAs}
	    ------------
	    @{" About... " link vprefs.menus.project.About}
	    ------------
	    @{" Quit " link vprefs.menus.project.Quit}

	Edit
	    @{" Reset To Defaults " link vprefs.menus.edit.ResetToDefaults}
	    @{" Last Saved " link vprefs.menus.edit.LastSaved}
	    @{" Restore " link vprefs.menus.edit.Restore}

	Settings
	    @{" Create Icons? " link vprefs.menus.settings.CreateIcons}

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.project.open "VPrefs Menus: Project/Open..."

	Load preferences from a file. A requester will appear to let
	you select a file name.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.project.saveas "VPrefs Menus: Project/Save As..."

	Save the currently displayed preferences into a file. A requester
	will appear to let you select a file name.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.project.about "VPrefs Menus: Project/About..."

	Open a requester that tells about @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist}.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.project.quit "VPrefs Menus: Project/Quit"

	Close the @{"VPrefs main window" link VPrefs.windows.main} without making any changes to the
	way @{"Ventriloquist" link Ventriloquist} operates. The settings in effect before you
	ran @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs} will remain in effect. This does the same thing as
	the @{"Cancel" link vprefs.windows.main.Cancelbutton} button in the VPrefs main window.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.edit.resettodefaults "VPrefs Menus: Edit/Reset To Defaults"

	Return to the default settings.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.edit.lastsaved "VPrefs Menus: Edit/Last Saved"

	Return to the last settings you saved.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.edit.restore "VPrefs Menus: Edit/Restore"

	Return to the settings shown when you first ran @{"VPrefs" link VPrefs}.

@endnode
@node vprefs.menus.settings.createicons "VPrefs Menus: Settings/Create Icons?"

	Specify whether or not icons will be created along with preset
	files created using the @{"Project/Save As..." link vprefs.menus.project.SaveAs} menu option.

@endnode
@node vreboot "VReboot Program"

VReboot is a utility program that will add a Reboot menu option to the
Workbench tools menu. This option, when selected, will reboot the Amiga
VReboot is running on, after verifying that you really want to reboot by
posting a requester.

If you're like me, you sometimes forget which machine you're actually
typing on when you're using Ventriloquist, and you sometimes reboot the
wrong one. If you get into the habit of using this program instead of
just hitting the keyboard, you can avoid rebooting the wrong machine.

	@{" VReboot Installation " link vreboot.installation}
	@{" VReboot Startup " link vreboot.startup}
	@{" VReboot Termination " link vreboot.termination}

@endnode
@node vreboot.installation "VReboot Installation"

Install @{"VReboot" link VReboot} on each Amiga where you want to use it by copying it to
your SYS:Utilities drawer, or to an alternate location of your own choice.
You can copy it by dragging the icon with the mouse, or by typing this
shell command:

	Copy VReboot#? SYS:Utilities

Modify your system to run VReboot at startup time by adding this command
to your S:user-startup file:

	Run >NIL: VReboot

@endnode
@node vreboot.startup "VReboot Startup"

@{"VReboot" link VReboot} can be started either from a shell or from Workbench.
It uses no command line options or Workbench tooltypes.

@endnode
@node vreboot.termination "VReboot Termination"

You can terminate @{"VReboot" link VReboot} two ways:

	1. Send it a Control-C, or
	2. Reboot the Amiga it's running on.

@endnode
